<section xml:id="sec_Permutations_Hints">
  <title>Hints for
  <q>Permutations</q>
  exercises</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      <xref ref="exercise_Permutations_64">Exercise</xref>: The first blank should be replaced by <m>k</m>
    </p>
    <p>
      <xref ref="exercise_Permutations_switchyard1">Exercise</xref>(c): Take advantage of the previous part.
    </p>
    <p>
      <xref ref="exercise_Permutations_switchyard2">Exercise</xref>(b): Note for instance that <m>(1 \;2 \; 3) = (1 \; 2) (2 \; 3)</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <xref ref="exercise_Permutations_switchyard2">Exercise</xref>(c): Note for instance that <m>(1 \;4 ) = (1 \; 2 \; 3 \; 4) \compose (1 \; 2 \; 3 )^{-1}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <xref ref="exercise_Permutations_Sn_even_odd">Exercise</xref>: Use the cycle structures you found in <xref ref="exercise_Permutations_cycle_types">Exercise</xref>
    </p>
    <p>
      <xref ref="exercise_Permutations_A_nGroupProps">Exercise</xref>(b): If you write <m>\sigma</m> as the product of transpositions <m>\tau_1 \cdots \tau_{n}</m>,
      then what is <m>\sigma^{-1}</m>?
    </p>
    <p>
      <xref ref="exercise_Permutations_A_nGroupProps">Exercise</xref>(c): If
      <m>\sigma = \tau_1 \cdots \tau_{n}</m> and <m>\mu = \lambda_1 \cdots \lambda_{m}</m>,
      then what about <m>\sigma \mu</m>?
    </p>
    <p>
      <xref ref="exercise_Permutations_prove">Exercise</xref>(a): If <m>\sigma</m> is even,
      then what about <m>(1 \; 2) \compose \sigma</m>?
    </p>
    <p>
      <xref ref="exercise_Permutations_prove">Exercise</xref>(b): If <m>\mu</m> is odd,
      then what about <m>(1 \; 2) \compose \mu</m>?
      Also, what is <m>f( (1 \; 2) \compose \mu )</m>?
    </p>
    <p>
      <xref ref="exercise_Permutations_prove">Exercise</xref>(c): If <m>(1 \; 2) \sigma_1 = (1 \; 2) \sigma_2</m>,
      then what can you conclude about <m>\sigma_1</m> and <m>\sigma_2</m>?
      Why are you able to conclude this?
    </p>
    <p>
      <xref ref="exercise_Permutations_Ad4">Exercise</xref>: Let <m>\ell</m> be the length of <m>\sigma</m>:
      then what is the order of <m>\sigma</m>?
      On the other hand, let <m>k</m> be the order of <m>\sigma^2</m>:
      then what do you know about <m>\sigma^{2k}</m>?
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection>
    <title>Hints for additional exercises (<xref ref="sec_Permutations_AdditionalExercises">Section</xref>)</title>
    <p>
      <xref ref="ex_Permutations_Ad1">Exercise</xref>: Consider the cycle structure.
    </p>
    <p>
      <xref ref="ex_Permutations_Ad2">Exercise</xref>: We know that <m>\sigma</m> can be written as the product of disjoint cycles.
      So let <m>\sigma_1, \sigma_2, \ldots \sigma_m</m> be disjoint cycles such that <m>\sigma = \sigma_1 \sigma_2 \ldots \sigma_m</m>,
      and let <m>\ell_j</m> be the length of the cycle <m>\sigma_j</m>.
      How many transpositions does it take to construct each of these disjoint cycles?
      And what is the largest possible value of the sum of <m>\ell_j</m>?
    </p>
    <p>
      <xref ref="ex_Permutations_Ad3">Exercise</xref>: Use the notation of the previous problem,
      and write a formula
      (in terms of <m>\ell_1 \ldots \ell_m</m> and <m>m</m>)
      for the number of transpositions it takes to construct <m>\sigma</m>.
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>